To address the memory limit exceeded issue and ensure efficient memory usage, we can implement a copy-on-write strategy for the vector data in the CustomVector class. This way, when a Memento is created, we only need to store a shared reference to the vector data, without actually copying it. The vector data will be copied only when necessary, such as when modifications are made to the vector.

Here's the updated code:

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <iostream>
#include <memory>

class Memento {
public:
    Memento(const std::shared_ptr<std::vector<int>>& data)
    : vector(data)
    {}

    const std::shared_ptr<std::vector<int>>& GetVector() const {
        return vector;
    }

private:
    std::shared_ptr<std::vector<int>> vector;
};

class CustomVector {
public:
    CustomVector() = default;

    void PushBack(int value) {
        if (!data.unique()) {
            copyData();
        }
        data->push_back(value);
    }

    void PopBack() {
        if (!data.unique()) {
            copyData();
        }
        if (!data->empty()) {
            data->pop_back();
        }
    }

    void Set(int index, int value) {
        if (!data.unique()) {
            copyData();
        }
        if (index >= 0 && index < data->size()) {
            (*data.get())[index] = value;
        }
    }

    int Get(int index) const {
        if (index >= 0 && index < data->size()) {
            return (*data.get())[index];
        }
        return 0;
    }

    Memento CreateMemento() const {
        return Memento(data);
    }

    void Restore(const Memento& memento) {
        data = memento.GetVector();
    }

private:
    std::shared_ptr<std::vector<int>> data = std::make_shared<std::vector<int>>();

    void copyData() {
        data = std::make_shared<std::vector<int>>(*data);
    }
};

int main() {
    CustomVector vector;
    vector.PushBack(1);
    vector.PushBack(2);
    vector.PushBack(3);

    Memento memento = vector.CreateMemento();

    vector.PopBack();
    vector.Set(0, 10);

    std::cout << vector.Get(0) << std::endl; // Output: 10

    vector.Restore(memento);

    std::cout << vector.Get(0) << std::endl; // Output: 1

    return 0;
}
```

With this implementation, the CustomVector class uses shared_ptr to store and manage the vector data. The copy-on-write strategy is applied by checking if the data is unique before making any modifications. If the data is not unique, indicating that other objects are referencing it, a copy is created before making any modifications. This ensures that the Mementos retain a valid reference to the original data without unnecessary copies.

